      "content": "yo can u help me with this pricing function? it's for a checkout system. it's getting super confusing with all the different tax rules i'm gonna just paste the logic and the tests i got so far. i need it to pass these specific cases for our UK/EU launch.\n\n```python\ndef calculate_final_price(order):\n    \"\"\"\n    order is a dict: \n    {\n        'base_price': float,\n        'region': str (e.g., 'UK', 'EU_DE', 'EU_FR'),\n        'discount_code': str or None,\n        'is_luxury': bool\n    }\n    \"\"\"\n    # implementation here\n    pass\n\n# Test cases provided by the finance team\ndef test_pricing():\n    # Case 1: UK Standard\n    order1 = {'base_price': 100.0, 'region': 'UK', 'discount_code': None, 'is_luxury': False}\n    assert calculate_final_price(order1) == 120.0  # 20% VAT\n    \n    # Case 2: EU Germany Luxury\n    order2 = {'base_price': 200.0, 'region': 'EU_DE', 'discount_code': 'SAVE10', 'is_luxury': True}\n    assert calculate_final_price(order2) == 233.0  # 19% VAT + 10% luxury tax, then 10% discount applied to total? actually let's say 233.0 is the expected\n    \n    # Case 3: EU France Standard with discount\n    order3 = {'base_price': 50.0, 'region': 'EU_FR', 'discount_code': 'PROMO', 'is_luxury': False}\n    assert calculate_final_price(order3) == 54.0 # 20% VAT, 10% discount\n    \n    print(\"All tests passed!\")\n\ntest_pricing()\n```\n\ni'm struggling with the order of operations on the discounts and taxes. can u write the function so it passes these? thanks",
